'''Matthew Sean Leon''' (born January 30, 1991) is a Canadian recording artist and record producer from [[Toronto, Ontario|Toronto]], [[Ontario]]. He is the founder of the IXXI Initiative, formed in 2012 in [[Toronto]]. In July 2013, Sean released his debut mixtape ''Ninelevenne, the Tragedy'' followed by his second project ''Narcissus, the Drowning of Ego'' on January 22, 2014.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Check Out Sean Leon's Trippy New Mixtape "Narcissus, The Drowning of Ego"|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|publisher=Complex Media|location=New York|date=February 6, 2014|author=Justin Davies}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopcanada.com/2013/07/sean-leon-ninelevenne-the-tragedy-mixtape/|title=Sean Leon – Ninelevenne, The Tragedy [Mixtape]|date=July 26, 2013|accessdate=August 24, 2017|author=Natasha Paolini}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2dopeboyz.com/2013/11/30/sean-leon-tanias-song-jordan-evans-jvell-boyce/e|title=Sean Leon – Tania's Song (prod. Jordan Evans & J'vell Boyce)|website=2dopeboyz.com|publisher=Illy|date=November 30, 2013|accessdate=April 25, 2014}}</ref>

Shortly after the release of ''Narcissus'', Sean began the year-long roll out of the compilation ''King Of The Wild Things''. That same spring of 2014 he introduced us to and began campaigning for the highly anticipated ''Black Sheep Nirvana''.

==Music career==
Sean Leon formed the IXXI Initiative based in Toronto, Ontario. His first mixtape, ''Ninelevenne, the Tragedy'', was released on July 23, 2013. On January 22, 2014, Sean released his second piece of work, ''Narcissus, the Drowning of Ego''. Both projects feature production by [[Jordan Evans (Producer)|Jordan Evans]], who was a part of the production team for [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]]'s ''Pound Cake'' featuring [[Jay Z]] on Drake's third studio album, ''[[Nothing Was the Same]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://thesource.com/2014/01/26/torontos-sean-leon-debuts-narcissus-the-drowning-of-ego/|title=Toronto's Sean Leon Debuts "Narcissus, The Drowning of Ego"|work=[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]|publisher=The Source|date=January 26, 2014|author=Haleema Khan}}</ref>

On May 25, 2015, Sean returned to the spotlight with the release of the [[WondaGurl]]-produced "This Ain't 2012", featuring River Tiber. When asked about the title of the song, Sean explained "It's the year before I started taking music seriously—in truth, I can't remember life before 2013 unless I'm high or drunk or emotional."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://noisey.vice.com/blog/sean-leon-wondagurl-river-tiber-this-aint-2012|title=Sean Leon Recruits Wondagurl and River Tiber for "This Ain't 2012" {{!}} NOISEY|website=NOISEY|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> A month later, Sean released "81", named after [[Kobe Bryant]]'s 81 point game against the [[Toronto Raptors]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://2dopeboyz.com/2015/06/26/sean-leon-81/|title=Sean Leon - "81"|date=June 26, 2015|website=2DOPEBOYZ|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> Produced by Eestbound, "81" was dubbed HipHopCanada's "Song of the Day" stating "Sean Leon (aka Maui Slim) is without a doubt one of the hottest artists coming out of Canada right now".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopcanada.com/2015/06/sean-leon-of-ixxis-kobe-bryant-influenced-single-81-is-our-song-of-the-day/|title=Sean Leon Of Ixxi’s Kobe Bryant-influenced Single, "81" Is Our Song Of The Day|date=June 25, 2015|website=HipHopCanada.com|accessdate=May 30, 2016}}</ref>

After a 4-month hiatus, Sean continued the hype surrounding ''Black Sheep Nirvana'' with a trio of freestyles over borrowed beats from [[The Weeknd]], [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]] and CMDWN.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thisiswalder.com/2015/11/sean-leon-has-dropped-3-new-tracks-wrist-freestyle-1-go-off-tell-your-friends/|title=Sean Leon has dropped 3 new tracks..."Wriss Freestyle", "1% (Go Off) & "Tell Your Fri(ends)"|website=thisiswalder.com|date=November 21, 2013|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> "Wriss Freestyle", "1% (Go Off) Freestyle" and "Tell Your Fri(ends) Freestyle" were all released for free via Sean's [[SoundCloud]] and [[Apple Music]] Connect pages.

In celebration of the [[NBA All-Star Weekend]], Sean teamed up with Green Label, a [[Mountain Dew]] venture, and fellow Toronto artists [[Jazz Cartier]] and [[WondaGurl]] for "Above the Rim".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://uproxx.com/smokingsection/sean-leon-jazz-cartier-above-the-rim-new-song/ |title= Sean Leon And Jazz Cartier Go Dumb On The WondaGurl-Produced ‘Above The Rim’ |website= [[Uproxx]] |language=en-GB |date= February 15, 2016 |accessdate= August 24, 2017}}</ref> "We did it in one night and it was dope," Leon said of the collaboration, sharing that his verse was a freestyle. "I work with WondaGurl all the time, and she's one of the few people I know that is actually super gifted, so I love working with her".<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://greenlabel.com/sound/sean-leon-is-ready-to-be-rap-king/ |title="I'm At The Point Where I Would Welcome a Diss Track from Anybody." Sean Leon Is Ready to Be Rap's New King {{!}} Green Label |date= February 13, 2016 |website= Green Label |language= en-US |accessdate= August 24, 2017}}</ref>

Following his appearance on [[Daniel Caesar]]'s ''Pilgrim's Paradise'' EP, Leon shared a new three-title release "Europe Freestyle/I Made It/Debt & Vendettas" produced by Sean Leon and co-produced by Yogidaproducer (Yojo). The single finds Leon "floating along on a rippled beat" while he "braces for the impending change in his rap career's bright future".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/03/15/sean-leon-europe-freestyle-i-made-it-debt-vendettas|author=Jordan Darville|title=Sean Leon Shares "Europe Freestyle/I Made It/Debt & Vendettas"|website=The FADER|date=March 15, 2016|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> A month later, Sean released two more WondaGurl-produced singles off ''Black Sheep Nirvana'' with "Deep End" and "Guard/God Up".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boi-1da.net/2016/04/07/sean-leon-hits-us-with-two-new-wondagurl-produced-tracks/|title=Sean Leon Hits Us With Two New WondaGurl Produced Tracks – Boi-1da.net|date=April 7, 2016|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref>

In April 2016, Sean released the self-produced "Matthew in the Middle" featuring IXXI compatriot [[Daniel Caesar]] with collaborative production efforts from Jovi, [[Jordan Evans (producer)|Jordan Evans]] and Jack Rochon. "The array of talent IXXI founder Sean Leon displays on every new release is mind-blowing. You can only define him as a pure artist" [[Boi-1da|Boi-1da.net]] remarked, calling the single a "beautiful record".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boi-1da.net/2016/04/13/sean-leon-gets-reflective-on-matthew-in-the-middle-with-daniel-caesar/|title=Sean Leon Gets Reflective On "Matthew In The Middle" With Daniel Caesar – Boi-1da.net|date=April 13, 2016|accessdate=May 30, 2016}}</ref> [[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] described the record as a "reflective masterpiece" noting "it's absurd that Sean Leon was left off of [[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]]'s list of "essential" post-Drake tracks, because half of the rappers in the city are currently imitating what he was doing last summer".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ca.complex.com/music/2016/04/best-canadian-songs-april-2016/sean-leon|author=Aaron Zorgel|title=Northern Touch: The Best Canadian Songs Of April - Sean Leon, "Matthew In The Middle" f/ Daniel Caesar|website=Complex CA|date=April 29, 2016|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref>

On April 20, 2016, Sean released the ''Black Sheep Nirvana'' single "Killin' Mind".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nahright.com/2016/04/20/sean-leon-killin-mind/|title=Sean Leon – Killin’ Mind {{!}} Nah Right|date=April 20, 2016|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> Produced by [[WondaGurl]], MADEAT2AM, Jack Rochon and Sean Leon himself, the single was well received and featured on [[Apple Music]]'s "Northern Touch", "Hot Up in the 6ix", "New Artists: Hip-Hop" and "Found Sounds: Hip-Hop" playlists created by Apple Music Hip-Hop [[curator]]s. A month later, Sean released "Maui Slim II", a follow up to "Maui Slim" off ''Ninelevenne, The Tragedy''. "Maui Slim II" had Sean sounding "as hungry as ever"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://the6track.com/2016/sean-leon-maui-slim-ii/|title=Sean Leon – Maui Slim II – The6Track|website=the6track.com|accessdate=2016-05-30}}</ref> with production by Jordan Evans, Mike DZL, Jovi and Jack Rochon, featuring background vocals from Rachel Piscione and violin from Aaron Cheung.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/sean_leon-game_7_flow_court_tomorrow_maui_slim_ii|author=Calum Slingerland|title=Sean Leon 'Game 7 Flow/Court Tomorrow' / 'Maui Slim II'|website=exclaim.ca|date=May 16, 2016|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref>

Following the [[Toronto Raptors]]' victory over the [[Miami Heat]] to advance to the [[NBA Eastern Conference]] finals, Leon released a nod to his hometown's winning team with "Game 7 Flow / Court Tomorrow" produced by DPAT.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/sean_leon-game_7_flow_court_tomorrow_maui_slim_ii|author=Calum Slingerland|title=Sean Leon 'Game 7 Flow/Court Tomorrow' / 'Maui Slim II'|website=exclaim.ca|accessdate=August 24, 2017}}</ref>

On November 29, 2017, Sean released an audio-film entitled "C.C.W.M.T.T".

==Discography==
===Albums & Mixtapes===
* ''Ninelevenne, the Tragedy'' (2013)
* ''Narcissus, The Drowning of Ego'' (2014)
* ''King of the Wild Things'' (2014)
* ''I Think You've Gone Mad (Or The Sins Of The Father)'' (2017)
* ''C.C.W.M.T.T.'' (2017)
* ''Sean Leon (The Death Of)'' (2018)

===Singles===
* "This Ain't 2012" (2015) <small>(produced by [[WondaGurl]])</small>
* "81" (2015) <small>(produced by Eestbound)</small>
* "Europe Freestyle / I Made It / Debt & Vendettas" (feat. Savannah Ré) (2016) <small>produced by Sean Leon and Yogidaproducer (YOJO))</small>
* "Deep End" (2016) <small>(produced by WondaGurl)</small>
* "Matthew in the Middle" (feat. [[Daniel Caesar]]) (2016) <small>(produced by Sean Leon, Jovi, [[Jordan Evans (producer)|Jordan Evans]] and Jack Rochon)</small>
* "Killin' Mind" (2016) <small>(produced by Sean Leon, WondaGurl, MADEAT2AM and Jack Rochon)</small>
* "Guard/God Up" (2016) <small>(produced by WondaGurl)</small>
* "Maui Slim II" (2016) <small>(produced by Jordan Evans, Mike DZL, Jovi and Jack Rochon)</small>
* "Game 7 Flow / Court Tomorrow" (2016) <small>(produced by DPAT)</small>

